Project Fundamentals of AIML: Cardio Good Fitness Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40

Submitted by: LARRY WEATHERFORD¶

Context¶

Cardio Good Fitness is a leading manufacturer of high-quality treadmills. The company offers three main products: the TM195, the TM498, and the TM798, which is their flagship product. With the rising demand for fitness in the market and an increasing number of competitors, Cardio Good Fitness wants to gain a better understanding of its existing customer profiles in order to develop more targeted marketing and product development strategies. They believe this will allow them to meet the needs and preferences of their customers, increase customer satisfaction, and drive revenue growth.


Objective¶

In order to gain insights into its customer profiles, Cardio Good Fitness has collected demographic and product usage information for each of its customers. The dataset includes variables such as age, gender, income, and miles run on the treadmill for each of the three products.

Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared the data with you. The requirement is to analyze the data and identify patterns in product usage and the key characteristics of customers by conducting exploratory data analysis (EDA) to come up with customer profiles.

The goal is to answer key questions such as:

  • What are the key characteristics of customers who purchase each product?
  • How does product usage vary by each group?


Data Description¶

The data is about customers of the treadmill product(s) of a retail store called Cardio Good Fitness. It contains the following variables-

  • Product - The model no. of the treadmill
  • Age - Age of the customer in no of years
  • Gender - Gender of the customer
  • Education - Education of the customer in no. of years
  • Marital Status - Marital status of the customer
  • Usage - Avg. number of times the customer wants to use the treadmill every week
  • Fitness - Self rated fitness score of the customer (5 - very fit, 1 - very unfit)
  • Income - Income of the customer
  • Miles- Miles that a customer expects to run

def my_countplot(df, column, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    #Define a function to build a countplot that will add % to the top of the bars
   
    ax = sns.countplot(x=column, data=df); #assign the plot to the variable ax

    # Add percentage labels to the top of each bar
    total = len(cardio["Product"])
    for p in ax.patches:
     percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
     x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.1
     y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
     ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size=10)
  
   # set labels and title
    plt.xlabel(xlabel);
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);
    plt.title(title);

    # show plot
    plt.show();

In [173]:
def histbox(data, x, figsize=(10, 4)):
    # function to display 2 subplots (histplot & boxplot) side by side
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=figsize)

    # Histplot
    ax_histplot = axes[0]  # Get the first subplot
    sns.set(style="whitegrid") #place a grid on this plot
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=x, kde=True, ax=ax_histplot)  # Create a histplot using the specified data and x-axis variable
    ax_histplot.set_title(f"Histplot for {x}")  # Set the title for the histplot

    # Boxplot
    ax_boxplot = axes[1]  # Get the second subplot
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=x, ax=ax_boxplot, color='green')  # Create a boxplot using the specified data and x-axis variable
    ax_boxplot.set_title(f"Boxplot for {x}")  # Set the title for the boxplot

    plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust the spacing between subplots
    plt.show();  # Display the subplots
    sns.set(style="white") #change the plot background to white to remove the grid

Question 6: Explore all the variables and provide observations on their distributions. (Generally, histograms, boxplots, countplots, etc. are used for univariate exploration.) [6 marks]¶

Before starting the EDA, I'm creating 2 new columns in the data to make reading some of the plots easier when using Income and Education variables. Group Income into 20K ranges and group Education into High School, College and Post Grad.

In [180]:
# Create a new column "Education Group" with grade level categories
# Categories are: High School = 12 or less, College = 13 - 16, PostGrad = >16
cardio['Education Group'] = pd.cut(cardio['Education'], bins=[0, 12, 16, float('inf')],
                                  labels=['High School', 'College', 'Post Grad'])

# Create a new column "Income Range" with 20K ranges for the Income (e.g. Income Ranges 10 - 20K, 20-40k, etc)
cardio['Income Range'] = pd.cut(cardio['Income'], bins=range(10000, 100001, 20000),
                               labels=["{} - {}K".format(i, i+19) for i in range(10, 90, 20)])

Conclusion & Recommendations for Each Model¶

Model TM798:¶

Key Characteristics for Model TM798:

Lowest selling model but used by the most affluent and highest educated customers. Average age of customers 29. 83% of customers are men. Average grade level is Post Grad. 58% of customers are married. Average usage: 4.7 times per week. Average self-rated fitness level: 4.6 out of 5. Average income: $75,000. Customers expect to run an average of 166 miles.

Recommendations for Model TM798:

  • Capitalize on the high-income and highly educated customer segment by focusing on premium features and high-end marketing strategies.

  • Consider expanding marketing efforts targeting women to increase the customer base.

  • Enhance the product's exclusivity and premium image to maintain its appeal to affluent customers.

  • Offer personalized training programs and advanced features to cater to customers with higher fitness levels.

  • Use this model to target neighbor gym franchises such as Anytime Fitness, Snap Fitness and Planet Fitness and try to win large national contracts.

Recommendations for Model TM498:

  • Invest in marketing campaigns that emphasize the affordability and value-for-money aspects of the product.

  • Consider introducing gender-specific marketing strategies to target both male and female customers effectively.

  • Offer diverse workout programs and options to accommodate customers with varying fitness levels.

Model TM195:¶

Key Characteristics for Model TM195:

The low end model that delivers on performance but with a budget. Average age of customers is 28. Both genders prefer this model equally. Average education level is Some College. 60% of customers are married. Average usage is 3 times per week. Average self-rated fitness level is 2.9 out of 5. Average income: $46,000.   • Offer customer support and guidance to assist those in the "some college" education level in maximizing the benefits of the product.

  • Provide options for customization and personalization to enhance the customer experience.

General Business Recommendations:¶

  • Conduct market research and hyper target prospects who have a college education, income levels above $50k, are physically fit, and are under between 25 and 50 years old. Especially market the TM798 product to this segment.

  • Submit customer surveys to solicit feedback and offer incentives (e.g. Discounts on accessories, future products) for customer referrals.

  • Develop targeted marketing campaigns to reach specific customer segments, such as women or individuals with specific fitness goals.

  • Develop a campaign targeting budget conscious men and women earning under $45K, with some college, between the ages of 22 - 40 and moderate fittness goals. The TM195 and TM498 products should be marketed to this segment.

  • Target national brand gyms to secure national contracts offering volumne pricing and maintainance plans for all 3 products.

  • Consider adding a video tablet, WiFi and studio workout streaming capabilites to future products so that an annual fitness subcription can be purchased to create a recurring revenue stream.

  • Explore partnerships with social media fitness influencers or experts to endorse the products and attract a broader audience.

  • Continuously monitor and analyze customer trends and preferences to stay ahead of the competition and adapt the product offerings accordingly. Provide exceptional customer service and after-sales support to build loyalty and encourage positive word-of-mouth recommendations.
